article.description:
Shawn Kemp had 12 points and 11 rebounds in his
second game subbing for the suspended Dale Davis and Portland beat
Boston 100-91 Monday night to win for the 15th time in 16 games.
article.headline: Blazers defeat Celtics for first time this year
article.linkText: Hot Blazers don't slow down against Celtics
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers are playing so well that they even beat the Boston Celtics in a 3-point contest. Bonzi Wells and Derek Anderson each hit a pair of 3s in the fourth quarter and the Blazers made 11 in all on Monday night to beat Boston 100-91, Portland's 15th win in its last 16 games. "We'd rather get inside and take high-percentage shots," said Wells, who hit a 3 with 11 seconds left to clinch the win and total 20 points for the night. "But they won't let you get anything in the lane." Shawn Kemp had 12 points and 11 rebounds in his second game subbing for the suspended Dale Davis, and Rasheed Wallace scored 18. "We owed Boston," Wells said. "They came into our house and beat us, and we wanted to return the favor." Paul Pierce had 28 points and eight rebounds, Antoine Walker had 19 and nine and Kenny Anderson had 14 points with nine rebounds and nine assists -- just missing his first triple-double in eight years. Boston had won seven in a row before losing to San Antonio on Saturday. The Celtics have taken 1,575 3-pointers -- by far more than any other team in the NBA, and over 500 more than Portland's 1,033. But when Boston clogged up the lane and forced the Blazers to shoot from outside, they didn't hesitate. Portland was 11-for-32 from 3-point range and 4-for-11 in the fourth quarter alone. Boston went 5-for-23 from long range, making 2-of-6 down the stretch. "I'm comfortable with our guys shooting 3s," Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said. "We've got some pretty good shooters. We've got a lot of guys who can shoot the ball." Kemp was starting for the second game in a row and just his second game of the season. On Saturday, when Davis began serving a two-game suspension for throwing a punch at Shawn Bradley, Kemp had a season-high 21 points and 14 rebounds. Portland led by 13 midway though the third and held a 77-69 lead with less than a minute left in the quarter before Walker made a layup and Pierce hit a 3-pointer with 2.9 seconds left. Pierce also hit a 3 to start the fourth and tie it at 77. But Portland got a pair of long-range jumpers from Derek Anderson to take a six-point lead. It was 84-81 when Pierce missed a 3 and Wells hit one, then Wells followed with a steal and breakaway slam to make it 89-81 with 6:09 left. "We allowed them to penetrate, then they kicked it out," Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "You can't stop a team that way." The game was tied at 37 with 7:48 left in the second period before Portland went on a 14-2 run. Wallace hit a 3-pointer, then stole the ball from Pierce to help set up Derek Anderson's 3-pointer. Anderson then stole the ball from Kenny Anderson and made one of two free throws. After Kenny Anderson made two free throws to make it 44-39, Wallace stole the ball from him to set up Ruben Patterson's two free throws. After a Celtics' timeout, Rick Brunson stole the ball from Walter McCarty and converted the fast break, then Wallace hit another 3 to make it 51-39. Game notes
Tony Battie made his first 10 shots against Portland this season before missing a baseline jumper in the second quarter. He was 7-for-7 in Portland, and he made his first three on Monday night. ... Kedrick Brown turned 21. ... Kenny Anderson has five career triple-doubles, all of them with New Jersey. His last was Jan. 22, 1994.
